{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Use British English|date=July 2014}}
'''Quentin H. Poole''' (born towards the end of 1957)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=QZtwYVWanQO8bcxpi8griA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> is an English [[Oboe|oboist]], conductor and former boy chorister, who served as Head Chorister of [[King's College, Cambridge]].<ref name="Liston">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxearthandliston.org.uk/2009/11/candlelight-services-at-liston/|title=Candlelight Services at Liston|work=Foxearth and Liston|accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref>
Poole was born in [[Surrey]], England, the son of [[Joseph W Poole|Joseph W. Poole]] and Esme B. Mounsey/Poole,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=T2h1oSc%2BLTQ%2B0xnDPXRTNQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> but he grew up, as the youngest of five children, at [[Coventry]], where his father was [[Precentor]] of [[Coventry Cathedral]].<ref name="DID">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/cd283a0e#p009ndfl |title=Desert Island Discs - Castaway : Quentin Poole |work=[[BBC Online]] |publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> He learned piano from the age of seven and trained under Sir [[David Willcocks]] at King's College,<ref name="NMC">{{cite web|url=http://nmcrec.co.uk/category/recording-artist/quentin-poole|title=Quentin Poole|publisher=[[NMC Recordings]]|accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> where he joined the choir aged nine.<ref name="DID" /> He also took up the flute there.<ref name="DID" /> He subsequently sang in the choir of [[The King's School, Canterbury]],<ref name="DID" /> and was a member of the [[National Youth Orchestra of Great Britain|National Youth Orchestra]].<ref name="NMC" />
He studied at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge|Corpus Christi College]], Cambridge and then at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] under [[Janet Craxton]].<ref name="NMC" />
Poole was a founder, member and oboist of the [[Endymion Ensemble]] and later its conductor.<ref name="NMC" /> He was also principal oboe for the [[City of London Sinfonia]] and other orchestras and chamber groups.<ref name="NMC" /> He was [[Director of Music]] of the [[Purcell School]] from 2001,<ref name="NMC" /> from which he was made redundant in 2013.<ref name="Stevens">{{cite web|url=http://www.classicalmusicmagazine.org/2013/10/purcell-school-makes-head-of-music-redundant-the-background/|title=Purcell School ‘deletes’ head of music role, likes to get kinky in the shrinky ‒ the background|last=Stevens|first=Alex|date=16 October 2013|work=[[Classical Music Magazine]]|accessdate=14 August 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814145455/http://www.classicalmusicmagazine.org/2013/10/purcell-school-makes-head-of-music-redundant-the-background/|archivedate=14 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was made a [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Music]] in 2004.<ref name="NMC" />
He appeared as a "castaway" on the [[BBC Radio]] programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 26 December 1970.<ref name="DID" /> He was 13 at the time; the programme's youngest guest.<ref name="DID" /> His picture was published in a contemporary issue of the ''[[Radio Times]]''.<ref name="DID" />
